Of course! The July 11 Movement refers to the popular demonstrations that took place in Brazil on July 11, 2013, during the so-called "June Days" of that year. The movement was articulated mainly by trade union centrals, social movements, student organizations, and workers from various categories. These demonstrations also became known as the "National Day of Struggles".

### Context
The 11 July Movement was a continuation of the large demonstrations that began in June 2013, but unlike those, it was formally organized by trade union organizations - such as CUT, Força Sindical, UGT, CTB, Nova Central, among others. While the June Journeys had a strong spontaneous and decentralized character, July 11 was more structured, with specific agendas and demands linked to the trade union and workers' movement.

### Agendas and demands
The main demands were:
- Reduction of the working day to 40 hours a week with no reduction in salary;
- An end to the social security factor;
- More investment in health and education;
- Quality public transportation;
- Readjustment of civil servants' salaries;
- Against Bill 4330, which extends outsourcing.

### Actions
The day was marked by strikes, protests, stoppages and demonstrations in various Brazilian cities. Sectors such as public transportation, banks, metalworkers and port workers joined the movement, impacting the normal functioning of services in various regions of the country.

### Meaning
The 11 July Movement was one of the largest trade union movements since the 1980s, showing the strength of the trade union federations in national mobilization and broadening discussions on labour rights, public services and social policies in Brazil.

